            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE) measures how efficiently gas or oil furnaces convert fuel into usable heat over an entire heating season. AFUE ratings represent the percentage of fuel that becomes heat for your home versus waste exhausted through venting. An 80% AFUE furnace converts 80 cents of every natural gas dollar into heat, wasting 20 cents through exhaust gases. Standard efficiency furnaces (80-82% AFUE) use conventional heat exchangers exhausting hot combustion gases through metal flue pipes, costing less upfront ($3,000-$4,500 installed) but consuming more fuel annually. Mid-efficiency furnaces (83-89% AFUE) use improved heat exchanger designs capturing more heat from combustion gases, offering moderate efficiency gains at slightly higher cost ($3,500-$5,000 installed). High-efficiency condensing furnaces (90-97% AFUE) extract so much heat that combustion gases condense into water (hence 'condensing furnaces'), requiring PVC vent pipes instead of metal flues, costing more upfront ($4,500-$6,500 installed) but delivering 15-20% lower operating costs annually worth $150-$250 savings in typical Tucson homes. Your heating bills directly reflect AFUE differences: a home spending $600 annually on heating with an 80% AFUE furnace would spend approximately $495 annually after upgrading to 96% AFUE equipment—$105 annual savings, $525 over five years, partially offsetting higher equipment cost while reducing environmental impact from lower fuel consumption."
